Dialogue: 0,0:14:00.41,0:14:03.26,Default,,0,0,0,,got to, required acceleration is
Dialogue: 0,0:14:03.80,0:14:05.85,Default,,0,0,0,,the amount that is required, and
Dialogue: 0,0:14:05.85,0:14:07.67,Default,,0,0,0,,it looks like what's probably
Dialogue: 0,0:14:07.67,0:14:10.68,Default,,0,0,0,,happening is that this value
Dialogue: 0,0:14:10.68,0:14:15.47,Default,,0,0,0,,here needs to be a little lower
Dialogue: 0,0:14:15.47,0:14:16.85,Default,,0,0,0,,so that it takes longer to jump.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:17.00,0:14:18.55,Default,,0,0,0,,So I don't have time at the
Dialogue: 0,0:14:18.55,0:14:20.59,Default,,0,0,0,,moment to demonstrate that or to
Dialogue: 0,0:14:20.59,0:14:21.84,Default,,0,0,0,,fix it, so I'm going to go ahead
Dialogue: 0,0:14:21.84,0:14:22.97,Default,,0,0,0,,and clear this breakpoint, click
Dialogue: 0,0:14:23.03,0:14:23.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Continue.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:33.83,0:14:34.25,Default,,0,0,0,,All right.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:34.44,0:14:35.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Looks like we lost the
Dialogue: 0,0:14:35.10,0:14:35.56,Default,,0,0,0,,connection.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:35.56,0:14:36.20,Default,,0,0,0,,That's no problem.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:36.23,0:14:37.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's see, actually, if we can
Dialogue: 0,0:14:37.62,0:14:37.98,Default,,0,0,0,,attach back to it.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:45.20,0:14:47.33,Default,,0,0,0,,So you'll notice in Xcode 9 we
Dialogue: 0,0:14:47.33,0:14:49.27,Default,,0,0,0,,now auto complete the process
Dialogue: 0,0:14:49.27,0:14:50.95,Default,,0,0,0,,name, we tokenize it, and you
Dialogue: 0,0:14:51.32,0:14:53.47,Default,,0,0,0,,get completion in this entry,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:53.47,0:14:53.98,Default,,0,0,0,,which is really nice.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:00.05,0:15:00.45,Default,,0,0,0,,All right.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:00.45,0:15:00.94,Default,,0,0,0,,We're back.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:01.52,0:15:07.62,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:15:08.12,0:15:08.68,Default,,0,0,0,,All right.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:08.68,0:15:09.69,Default,,0,0,0,,So there's one more thing that
Dialogue: 0,0:15:09.69,0:15:12.02,Default,,0,0,0,,I'd like to take a look at, and
Dialogue: 0,0:15:12.47,0:15:13.70,Default,,0,0,0,,that's a performance problem
Dialogue: 0,0:15:14.00,0:15:15.74,Default,,0,0,0,,that my colleague was pointing
Dialogue: 0,0:15:15.74,0:15:15.87,Default,,0,0,0,,out.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:15.87,0:15:17.48,Default,,0,0,0,,We were tapping around with the
Dialogue: 0,0:15:17.48,0:15:18.71,Default,,0,0,0,,SolarSystem and they noticed
Dialogue: 0,0:15:19.31,0:15:20.64,Default,,0,0,0,,when they tapped on Jupiter,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:21.90,0:15:23.45,Default,,0,0,0,,there's a bit of a lag.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:23.62,0:15:25.38,Default,,0,0,0,,The camera doesn't show it
Dialogue: 0,0:15:25.38,0:15:26.85,Default,,0,0,0,,really well, but you can kind of
Dialogue: 0,0:15:26.85,0:15:28.50,Default,,0,0,0,,see a pause and, you know,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:28.71,0:15:31.98,Default,,0,0,0,,that's impacting battery life
Dialogue: 0,0:15:32.02,0:15:32.63,Default,,0,0,0,,and we just kind of want to take
Dialogue: 0,0:15:32.66,0:15:33.50,Default,,0,0,0,,a look and see if we can figure
Dialogue: 0,0:15:33.53,0:15:33.98,Default,,0,0,0,,out what's going on.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:38.05,0:15:38.81,Default,,0,0,0,,So I'm going to go to the Energy
Dialogue: 0,0:15:38.81,0:15:39.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Impact Gauge.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:39.48,0:15:40.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Sure enough it's high.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:40.29,0:15:41.50,Default,,0,0,0,,You'll notice that this has been
Dialogue: 0,0:15:41.50,0:15:42.90,Default,,0,0,0,,redesigned in Xcode 9 to give
Dialogue: 0,0:15:42.90,0:15:44.47,Default,,0,0,0,,you a much better look at
Dialogue: 0,0:15:44.47,0:15:46.58,Default,,0,0,0,,exactly where your energy is
Dialogue: 0,0:15:46.58,0:15:47.75,Default,,0,0,0,,being consumed by your app.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:47.75,0:15:50.18,Default,,0,0,0,,So in this case we've got the
Dialogue: 0,0:15:50.18,0:15:51.83,Default,,0,0,0,,CPU, which I think is probably
Dialogue: 0,0:15:51.83,0:15:53.07,Default,,0,0,0,,taking a little bit more than it
Dialogue: 0,0:15:53.07,0:15:55.74,Default,,0,0,0,,should for a GPU-oriented app,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:55.93,0:15:57.61,Default,,0,0,0,,and it goes up every time I
Dialogue: 0,0:15:57.61,0:15:58.19,Default,,0,0,0,,touch that.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:58.51,0:16:00.96,Default,,0,0,0,,So what do we do when we need to
Dialogue: 0,0:16:00.96,0:16:02.12,Default,,0,0,0,,dig deeper into performance
Dialogue: 0,0:16:02.12,0:16:02.55,Default,,0,0,0,,problems?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:02.76,0:16:03.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, we go into Instruments.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:04.14,0:16:05.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, some of you may not know
Dialogue: 0,0:16:05.39,0:16:06.56,Default,,0,0,0,,this, but there's a really cool
Dialogue: 0,0:16:06.56,0:16:07.42,Default,,0,0,0,,feature in Xcode.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:07.81,0:16:08.91,Default,,0,0,0,,If you've ever had to like --
Dialogue: 0,0:16:10.24,0:16:11.30,Default,,0,0,0,,you know, you're debugging a bug
Dialogue: 0,0:16:11.30,0:16:12.24,Default,,0,0,0,,and you're like, oh, man,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:12.24,0:16:13.28,Default,,0,0,0,,there's a performance problem,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:13.56,0:16:15.14,Default,,0,0,0,,all right, let me, you know, go
Dialogue: 0,0:16:15.14,0:16:16.13,Default,,0,0,0,,to Instruments and start it
Dialogue: 0,0:16:16.13,0:16:17.39,Default,,0,0,0,,again, you don't have to do
Dialogue: 0,0:16:17.39,0:16:17.65,Default,,0,0,0,,that.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:17.65,0:16:18.71,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm going to click the Time
Dialogue: 0,0:16:18.71,0:16:20.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Profile button and this is going
Dialogue: 0,0:16:20.24,0:16:21.90,Default,,0,0,0,,to transfer the debug session to
Dialogue: 0,0:16:21.90,0:16:22.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Instruments and keep the app
Dialogue: 0,0:16:23.03,0:16:23.39,Default,,0,0,0,,going.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:23.68,0:16:24.82,Default,,0,0,0,,This is great if you've got an
Dialogue: 0,0:16:24.82,0:16:26.30,Default,,0,0,0,,app in state and you need to
Dialogue: 0,0:16:26.30,0:16:27.47,Default,,0,0,0,,jump over to Instruments and see
Dialogue: 0,0:16:27.47,0:16:28.24,Default,,0,0,0,,what's going on.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:28.45,0:16:29.89,Default,,0,0,0,,So we've started Instruments.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:29.89,0:16:30.80,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm going to move the window
Dialogue: 0,0:16:30.80,0:16:31.66,Default,,0,0,0,,over, give us a little bit of a
Dialogue: 0,0:16:31.66,0:16:31.98,Default,,0,0,0,,better view.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:36.38,0:16:38.78,Default,,0,0,0,,And we see that we are in the
Dialogue: 0,0:16:38.81,0:16:40.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Instruments default strategy,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:40.41,0:16:41.68,Default,,0,0,0,,which just says the CPU Usage
Dialogue: 0,0:16:41.75,0:16:43.97,Default,,0,0,0,,and the Life Cycle, but new in
Dialogue: 0,0:16:43.97,0:16:45.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Instruments for Xcode 9 is this
Dialogue: 0,0:16:45.48,0:16:46.24,Default,,0,0,0,,All strategy.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:46.49,0:16:47.62,Default,,0,0,0,,So this is the time profile
Dialogue: 0,0:16:47.62,0:16:49.47,Default,,0,0,0,,instrument, but if I click All,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:49.67,0:16:52.21,Default,,0,0,0,,I see all of the threads and the
Dialogue: 0,0:16:52.21,0:16:54.01,Default,,0,0,0,,cores and I get the big picture
Dialogue: 0,0:16:54.56,0:16:55.01,Default,,0,0,0,,of the app.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:55.23,0:16:55.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Really, really useful.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:55.98,0:16:57.23,Default,,0,0,0,,So let's see if we can reproduce
Dialogue: 0,0:16:57.23,0:16:57.98,Default,,0,0,0,,the problem.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:58.52,0:17:03.73,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:17:04.23,0:17:04.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Here we go.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:09.27,0:17:09.56,Default,,0,0,0,,All right.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:09.56,0:17:10.72,Default,,0,0,0,,So we've clearly seen that
Dialogue: 0,0:17:10.72,0:17:11.33,Default,,0,0,0,,there's an issue.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:12.07,0:17:13.16,Default,,0,0,0,,We've got this spike here.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:13.41,0:17:15.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, sometimes you want to just
Dialogue: 0,0:17:15.88,0:17:17.38,Default,,0,0,0,,dig directly into that and look
Dialogue: 0,0:17:17.38,0:17:18.25,Default,,0,0,0,,at the call stacks, but
Dialogue: 0,0:17:18.25,0:17:19.54,Default,,0,0,0,,sometimes what you want to do is
Dialogue: 0,0:17:19.54,0:17:22.55,Default,,0,0,0,,correlate that spike to what CPU
Dialogue: 0,0:17:22.55,0:17:26.30,Default,,0,0,0,,it's on, other threads, and you
Dialogue: 0,0:17:26.30,0:17:27.20,Default,,0,0,0,,know how to do that, right, you
Dialogue: 0,0:17:27.20,0:17:28.27,Default,,0,0,0,,just scroll, back it up, and you
Dialogue: 0,0:17:28.27,0:17:29.39,Default,,0,0,0,,look and you see, oh, is there
Dialogue: 0,0:17:29.39,0:17:31.02,Default,,0,0,0,,another one, well, I'm not sure.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:31.40,0:17:33.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, for Instruments in Xcode 9
Dialogue: 0,0:17:33.25,0:17:34.30,Default,,0,0,0,,there is a much better way.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:34.79,0:17:36.04,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm going to pin this track,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:36.41,0:17:38.14,Default,,0,0,0,,right, and pinning the track
Dialogue: 0,0:17:39.04,0:17:40.49,Default,,0,0,0,,actually puts a copy of that
Dialogue: 0,0:17:40.49,0:17:41.92,Default,,0,0,0,,track at the bottom and it's
Dialogue: 0,0:17:41.92,0:17:42.28,Default,,0,0,0,,fixed.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:42.28,0:17:44.13,Default,,0,0,0,,So now I can scroll up and down
Dialogue: 0,0:17:44.32,0:17:46.88,Default,,0,0,0,,and I can correlate what other
Dialogue: 0,0:17:47.10,0:17:48.25,Default,,0,0,0,,tracks are sharing that
Dialogue: 0,0:17:48.67,0:17:49.98,Default,,0,0,0,,performance characteristic
Dialogue: 0,0:17:50.02,0:17:50.70,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:17:50.69,0:17:51.37,Default,,0,0,0,,.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:51.37,0:17:52.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah, it's really, really cool.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:54.07,0:17:55.81,Default,,0,0,0,,And not only can you just see
Dialogue: 0,0:17:55.81,0:17:57.48,Default,,0,0,0,,the spikes, but I think it's
Dialogue: 0,0:17:57.48,0:17:58.90,Default,,0,0,0,,also important to know what's
Dialogue: 0,0:17:58.90,0:17:59.55,Default,,0,0,0,,not happening.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:59.64,0:18:01.24,Default,,0,0,0,,So being able to see that all of
Dialogue: 0,0:18:01.24,0:18:02.38,Default,,0,0,0,,these are not correlated
Dialogue: 0,0:18:02.78,0:18:03.75,Default,,0,0,0,,obviously gives you information
Dialogue: 0,0:18:03.75,0:18:03.98,Default,,0,0,0,,as well.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:10.06,0:18:11.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay. So what we've just seen
Dialogue: 0,0:18:12.05,0:18:16.32,Default,,0,0,0,,are a few things that you can do
Dialogue: 0,0:18:16.61,0:18:17.66,Default,,0,0,0,,with wireless development in
Dialogue: 0,0:18:17.66,0:18:18.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Xcode 9.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:20.88,0:18:22.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Don't need that.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:22.67,0:18:25.09,Default,,0,0,0,,So this just scratches the
Dialogue: 0,0:18:25.09,0:18:26.63,Default,,0,0,0,,surface because, as Chris said,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:26.63,0:18:28.09,Default,,0,0,0,,there's lots of times,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:28.16,0:18:30.19,Default,,0,0,0,,especially today, when the apps
Dialogue: 0,0:18:30.19,0:18:32.53,Default,,0,0,0,,we're developing, they are not
Dialogue: 0,0:18:32.97,0:18:35.14,Default,,0,0,0,,you sitting down and consuming
Dialogue: 0,0:18:35.14,0:18:36.99,Default,,0,0,0,,content while you're on the bus.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:37.07,0:18:38.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Those apps still exist, of
Dialogue: 0,0:18:38.15,0:18:40.02,Default,,0,0,0,,course, but more and more of our
Dialogue: 0,0:18:40.02,0:18:41.55,Default,,0,0,0,,apps are physical, they're
Dialogue: 0,0:18:41.55,0:18:42.76,Default,,0,0,0,,interacting in the real world,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:43.12,0:18:45.46,Default,,0,0,0,,and sometimes you get reports
Dialogue: 0,0:18:45.46,0:18:46.35,Default,,0,0,0,,and you want to reproduce
Dialogue: 0,0:18:46.35,0:18:47.81,Default,,0,0,0,,problems that you can only
Dialogue: 0,0:18:47.81,0:18:49.57,Default,,0,0,0,,reproduce in the real world.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:49.88,0:18:51.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Sometimes you have performance
Dialogue: 0,0:18:51.12,0:18:52.37,Default,,0,0,0,,problems where you need a tool
Dialogue: 0,0:18:52.37,0:18:53.83,Default,,0,0,0,,like Instruments to really dig
Dialogue: 0,0:18:53.83,0:18:55.74,Default,,0,0,0,,deep into your performance and
Dialogue: 0,0:18:55.74,0:18:57.10,Default,,0,0,0,,you want to do that in the real
Dialogue: 0,0:18:57.10,0:18:57.49,Default,,0,0,0,,world.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:57.63,0:18:59.12,Default,,0,0,0,,And with wireless development
Dialogue: 0,0:18:59.17,0:18:59.44,Default,,0,0,0,,you can.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:59.44,0:19:00.24,Default,,0,0,0,,And with that, I'd like to hand
Dialogue: 0,0:19:00.24,0:19:00.96,Default,,0,0,0,,it back to Chris.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:01.52,0:19:07.79,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:19:08.29,0:19:08.85,Default,,0,0,0,,>> Thanks, Breckin.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:09.26,0:19:10.09,Default,,0,0,0,,What a fun demo.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:10.44,0:19:11.74,Default,,0,0,0,,All right.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:11.74,0:19:13.02,Default,,0,0,0,,I'd like to move on to talking
Dialogue: 0,0:19:13.02,0:19:15.02,Default,,0,0,0,,about enhancements we've made in
Dialogue: 0,0:19:15.02,0:19:15.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Xcode for working with
Dialogue: 0,0:19:15.98,0:19:16.68,Default,,0,0,0,,breakpoints.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:17.14,0:19:19.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Some of you may not know, but in
Dialogue: 0,0:19:19.70,0:19:21.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Xcode breakpoints have a lot of
Dialogue: 0,0:19:21.27,0:19:22.06,Default,,0,0,0,,flexibility.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:22.71,0:19:23.74,Default,,0,0,0,,There are options that you can
Dialogue: 0,0:19:23.74,0:19:25.02,Default,,0,0,0,,set to customize the way that
Dialogue: 0,0:19:25.02,0:19:25.59,Default,,0,0,0,,they behave.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:26.23,0:19:28.10,Default,,0,0,0,,To do this just double click on
Dialogue: 0,0:19:28.10,0:19:29.86,Default,,0,0,0,,a breakpoint and you'll see the
Dialogue: 0,0:19:29.86,0:19:31.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Breakpoint Editor popover.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:31.72,0:19:33.63,Default,,0,0,0,,From here you can set options
Dialogue: 0,0:19:33.63,0:19:35.78,Default,,0,0,0,,such as defining a condition so
Dialogue: 0,0:19:36.29,0:19:37.63,Default,,0,0,0,,the breakpoint will only trigger
Dialogue: 0,0:19:37.63,0:19:38.84,Default,,0,0,0,,if that condition evaluates
Dialogue: 0,0:19:38.84,0:19:40.46,Default,,0,0,0,,true; and you can define
Dialogue: 0,0:19:40.84,0:19:42.40,Default,,0,0,0,,breakpoint actions, such as
Dialogue: 0,0:19:42.40,0:19:43.76,Default,,0,0,0,,logging variables, executing
Dialogue: 0,0:19:43.76,0:19:45.29,Default,,0,0,0,,debugger commands for you and
Dialogue: 0,0:19:45.35,0:19:46.11,Default,,0,0,0,,playing sounds.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:46.57,0:19:47.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, these options have been in
Dialogue: 0,0:19:47.80,0:19:49.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Xcode for some time, but over
Dialogue: 0,0:19:49.83,0:19:51.08,Default,,0,0,0,,the past year the team have been
Dialogue: 0,0:19:51.08,0:19:52.21,Default,,0,0,0,,making some enhancements to the
Dialogue: 0,0:19:52.21,0:19:53.92,Default,,0,0,0,,UI to make them easier to work
Dialogue: 0,0:19:53.92,0:19:54.06,Default,,0,0,0,,with.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:55.02,0:19:56.95,Default,,0,0,0,,The first of these, we've added
Dialogue: 0,0:19:56.95,0:19:57.78,Default,,0,0,0,,code completion to all the
Dialogue: 0,0:19:57.85,0:19:58.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Breakpoint Editor text fields.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:59.52,0:20:05.59,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:20:06.09,0:20:07.25,Default,,0,0,0,,So now in the Breakpoint Editor,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:07.58,0:20:10.77,Default,,0,0,0,,when editing expressions in the
Dialogue: 0,0:20:10.77,0:20:12.17,Default,,0,0,0,,condition field and the
Dialogue: 0,0:20:12.17,0:20:13.62,Default,,0,0,0,,breakpoint action fields, you
Dialogue: 0,0:20:13.62,0:20:14.99,Default,,0,0,0,,get full code completion, the
Dialogue: 0,0:20:14.99,0:20:16.54,Default,,0,0,0,,same as you'd expect from the
Dialogue: 0,0:20:16.54,0:20:18.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Source Editor and the Debugger
Dialogue: 0,0:20:18.48,0:20:18.96,Default,,0,0,0,,Console.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:19.53,0:20:21.66,Default,,0,0,0,,The next thing we wanted to do
Dialogue: 0,0:20:21.66,0:20:23.37,Default,,0,0,0,,was make finding breakpoints
Dialogue: 0,0:20:23.37,0:20:25.20,Default,,0,0,0,,with options set on them much
Dialogue: 0,0:20:25.20,0:20:27.79,Default,,0,0,0,,easier, so in Xcode 9, for any
Dialogue: 0,0:20:27.79,0:20:29.22,Default,,0,0,0,,breakpoints that have options
Dialogue: 0,0:20:29.22,0:20:30.20,Default,,0,0,0,,set on them, you'll see this
Dialogue: 0,0:20:30.20,0:20:31.24,Default,,0,0,0,,alternate indicator with a
Dialogue: 0,0:20:31.24,0:20:31.98,Default,,0,0,0,,triangle at the end.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:32.52,0:20:36.71,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:20:37.21,0:20:38.94,Default,,0,0,0,,So this indicates that that
Dialogue: 0,0:20:38.94,0:20:40.51,Default,,0,0,0,,breakpoint has one or more
Dialogue: 0,0:20:40.51,0:20:41.99,Default,,0,0,0,,options set on it.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:41.99,0:20:43.78,Default,,0,0,0,,This makes it really easy to see
Dialogue: 0,0:20:43.78,0:20:45.19,Default,,0,0,0,,at a glance, when looking at
Dialogue: 0,0:20:45.41,0:20:46.73,Default,,0,0,0,,either the Breakpoint Navigator
Dialogue: 0,0:20:47.04,0:20:48.55,Default,,0,0,0,,or the Source Editor, which of
Dialogue: 0,0:20:48.55,0:20:49.89,Default,,0,0,0,,those breakpoints have options
Dialogue: 0,0:20:49.89,0:20:51.25,Default,,0,0,0,,set on them.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:51.69,0:20:53.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Furthermore, just mouse over the
Dialogue: 0,0:20:53.33,0:20:54.76,Default,,0,0,0,,breakpoint and a tooltip will
Dialogue: 0,0:20:54.76,0:20:55.92,Default,,0,0,0,,show you a summary of the
Dialogue: 0,0:20:55.92,0:20:57.00,Default,,0,0,0,,options that have been set on
Dialogue: 0,0:20:57.00,0:20:57.54,Default,,0,0,0,,the breakpoint.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:58.05,0:20:59.01,Default,,0,0,0,,This should make finding the
Dialogue: 0,0:20:59.01,0:21:00.04,Default,,0,0,0,,breakpoint you're looking for
Dialogue: 0,0:21:00.24,0:21:00.86,Default,,0,0,0,,much easier.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:01.59,0:21:02.52,Default,,0,0,0,,And speaking of finding
Dialogue: 0,0:21:02.52,0:21:04.66,Default,,0,0,0,,breakpoints, we've also enhanced
Dialogue: 0,0:21:04.84,0:21:06.25,Default,,0,0,0,,the Breakpoint Navigator filter
Dialogue: 0,0:21:06.25,0:21:08.30,Default,,0,0,0,,field by adding deep filtering.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:08.75,0:21:10.43,Default,,0,0,0,,This means that it now searches
Dialogue: 0,0:21:10.72,0:21:12.73,Default,,0,0,0,,your query across all of the
Dialogue: 0,0:21:12.73,0:21:13.94,Default,,0,0,0,,text fields in the Breakpoint
Dialogue: 0,0:21:13.94,0:21:14.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Editor.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:14.60,0:21:15.68,Default,,0,0,0,,So you can match on condition
Dialogue: 0,0:21:15.68,0:21:16.91,Default,,0,0,0,,fields and any of the action
Dialogue: 0,0:21:16.91,0:21:18.27,Default,,0,0,0,,fields and expressions that
Dialogue: 0,0:21:18.27,0:21:19.19,Default,,0,0,0,,you've set in those.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:20.14,0:21:21.86,Default,,0,0,0,,This makes finding breakpoints
Dialogue: 0,0:21:22.06,0:21:23.27,Default,,0,0,0,,much more powerful and much
Dialogue: 0,0:21:23.27,0:21:24.59,Default,,0,0,0,,easier in the Breakpoint
Dialogue: 0,0:21:24.64,0:21:25.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Navigator.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:26.45,0:21:27.40,Default,,0,0,0,,So if you haven't been using
Dialogue: 0,0:21:27.40,0:21:28.68,Default,,0,0,0,,breakpoint options, give them a
Dialogue: 0,0:21:28.68,0:21:28.95,Default,,0,0,0,,try.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:28.95,0:21:29.76,Default,,0,0,0,,They can add a lot of
Dialogue: 0,0:21:29.96,0:21:31.58,Default,,0,0,0,,flexibility and customization to
Dialogue: 0,0:21:31.58,0:21:32.53,Default,,0,0,0,,your debugging workflow, and now
Dialogue: 0,0:21:32.53,0:21:32.98,Default,,0,0,0,,they're easier to use.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:37.22,0:21:38.68,Default,,0,0,0,,I'd like to move on to talking
Dialogue: 0,0:21:38.68,0:21:40.14,Default,,0,0,0,,about user interface debugging.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:41.43,0:21:43.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, when building UI, View
Dialogue: 0,0:21:43.30,0:21:44.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Controller is playing an
Dialogue: 0,0:21:44.14,0:21:47.09,Default,,0,0,0,,important role in how you
Dialogue: 0,0:21:47.09,0:21:48.25,Default,,0,0,0,,structure your code and your
Dialogue: 0,0:21:48.25,0:21:49.05,Default,,0,0,0,,storyboards.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:49.89,0:21:51.99,Default,,0,0,0,,View controllers manage and lay
Dialogue: 0,0:21:51.99,0:21:53.24,Default,,0,0,0,,out portions of the view tree
Dialogue: 0,0:21:53.69,0:21:55.49,Default,,0,0,0,,and are responsible for handling
Dialogue: 0,0:21:55.49,0:21:56.82,Default,,0,0,0,,transitions between screens.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:57.71,0:21:58.80,Default,,0,0,0,,So when debugging your UI,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:58.80,0:22:00.05,Default,,0,0,0,,wouldn't it be great to be able
Dialogue: 0,0:22:00.05,0:22:01.58,Default,,0,0,0,,to navigate that view hierarchy
Dialogue: 0,0:22:01.85,0:22:03.65,Default,,0,0,0,,by focusing on the View
Dialogue: 0,0:22:03.65,0:22:05.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Controller structure and to also
Dialogue: 0,0:22:05.48,0:22:06.97,Default,,0,0,0,,be able to find view controllers
Dialogue: 0,0:22:07.15,0:22:08.61,Default,,0,0,0,,that are responsible for parts
Dialogue: 0,0:22:08.61,0:22:09.16,Default,,0,0,0,,of the view tree.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:10.16,0:22:11.91,Default,,0,0,0,,We thought so, too, so in Xcode
Dialogue: 0,0:22:11.91,0:22:13.52,Default,,0,0,0,,9 view controllers are now
Dialogue: 0,0:22:13.52,0:22:15.29,Default,,0,0,0,,included as part of the view
Dialogue: 0,0:22:15.29,0:22:15.98,Default,,0,0,0,,hierarchy when debugging.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:16.52,0:22:21.31,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:22:21.81,0:22:22.96,Default,,0,0,0,,Inspect your view hierarchy like
Dialogue: 0,0:22:23.00,0:22:24.26,Default,,0,0,0,,you always have been, but now
Dialogue: 0,0:22:24.26,0:22:25.74,Default,,0,0,0,,you can expect to find View
Dialogue: 0,0:22:25.74,0:22:27.38,Default,,0,0,0,,controllers in the Debug
Dialogue: 0,0:22:27.38,0:22:29.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Navigator inserted as parents of
Dialogue: 0,0:22:29.44,0:22:30.66,Default,,0,0,0,,the views that they manage.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:31.39,0:22:32.87,Default,,0,0,0,,This makes it really easy to
Dialogue: 0,0:22:32.87,0:22:34.69,Default,,0,0,0,,navigate the view hierarchy by
Dialogue: 0,0:22:34.69,0:22:36.47,Default,,0,0,0,,first focusing on the high-level
Dialogue: 0,0:22:36.63,0:22:38.23,Default,,0,0,0,,View Controller structure to
Dialogue: 0,0:22:38.23,0:22:39.43,Default,,0,0,0,,find the area of the view tree
Dialogue: 0,0:22:39.43,0:22:40.87,Default,,0,0,0,,that you're looking to debug and
Dialogue: 0,0:22:40.87,0:22:42.44,Default,,0,0,0,,then focusing in on individual
Dialogue: 0,0:22:42.44,0:22:42.92,Default,,0,0,0,,views.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:43.41,0:22:45.71,Default,,0,0,0,,View controllers are represented
Dialogue: 0,0:22:45.71,0:22:47.87,Default,,0,0,0,,visually in the Canvas as well.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:48.78,0:22:50.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Xcode renders banners for View
Dialogue: 0,0:22:50.75,0:22:52.05,Default,,0,0,0,,controllers above the views that
Dialogue: 0,0:22:52.05,0:22:52.59,Default,,0,0,0,,they manage.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:53.32,0:22:55.30,Default,,0,0,0,,This is great for visualizing
Dialogue: 0,0:22:55.39,0:22:56.66,Default,,0,0,0,,the View Controller boundaries
Dialogue: 0,0:22:56.66,0:22:58.32,Default,,0,0,0,,in that view tree and makes it
Dialogue: 0,0:22:58.32,0:22:59.84,Default,,0,0,0,,much easier to find the view
Dialogue: 0,0:22:59.84,0:23:01.20,Default,,0,0,0,,controllers responsible for a
Dialogue: 0,0:23:01.20,0:23:03.98,Default,,0,0,0,,particular view.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:04.24,0:23:05.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Select a View Controller and
Dialogue: 0,0:23:05.56,0:23:06.96,Default,,0,0,0,,you'll see its properties in the
Dialogue: 0,0:23:06.96,0:23:08.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Inspectors, and this helps you
Dialogue: 0,0:23:08.27,0:23:09.36,Default,,0,0,0,,when you're debugging View
Dialogue: 0,0:23:09.36,0:23:10.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Controller specific issues.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:11.25,0:23:12.81,Default,,0,0,0,,It includes the View Controller
Dialogue: 0,0:23:12.81,0:23:14.13,Default,,0,0,0,,parent and child relationships,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:14.61,0:23:16.08,Default,,0,0,0,,which is great for debugging
Dialogue: 0,0:23:16.08,0:23:17.15,Default,,0,0,0,,View Controller containment
Dialogue: 0,0:23:17.15,0:23:17.67,Default,,0,0,0,,issues.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:19.24,0:23:20.28,Default,,0,0,0,,So now that view controllers are
Dialogue: 0,0:23:20.28,0:23:21.68,Default,,0,0,0,,included as part of the view
Dialogue: 0,0:23:21.68,0:23:23.10,Default,,0,0,0,,hierarchy when debugging, it
Dialogue: 0,0:23:23.10,0:23:24.51,Default,,0,0,0,,makes it much easier to navigate
Dialogue: 0,0:23:24.51,0:23:26.25,Default,,0,0,0,,that hierarchy and to help you
Dialogue: 0,0:23:26.25,0:23:28.17,Default,,0,0,0,,to solve View Controller-related
Dialogue: 0,0:23:28.17,0:23:28.67,Default,,0,0,0,,issues.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:29.21,0:23:32.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, not all user interfaces are
Dialogue: 0,0:23:32.35,0:23:34.30,Default,,0,0,0,,built using UIKit and AppKit.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:35.38,0:23:37.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Some designs may require custom
Dialogue: 0,0:23:37.34,0:23:40.79,Default,,0,0,0,,UI with rich interactions and
Dialogue: 0,0:23:40.79,0:23:41.67,Default,,0,0,0,,custom layouts.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:42.17,0:23:44.15,Default,,0,0,0,,One option to do this is using
Dialogue: 0,0:23:44.15,0:23:44.72,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:46.34,0:23:47.80,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit is a 2D graphics
Dialogue: 0,0:23:47.80,0:23:48.87,Default,,0,0,0,,framework and it's available
Dialogue: 0,0:23:48.87,0:23:50.42,Default,,0,0,0,,across all of Apple's platforms.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:50.94,0:23:52.28,Default,,0,0,0,,It's great for building games,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:52.28,0:23:52.78,Default,,0,0,0,,of course.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:52.84,0:23:53.88,Default,,0,0,0,,It's also great for building
Dialogue: 0,0:23:53.88,0:23:54.94,Default,,0,0,0,,this kind of custom UI.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:54.94,0:23:57.58,Default,,0,0,0,,So we wanted to provide the same
Dialogue: 0,0:23:57.58,0:23:58.87,Default,,0,0,0,,kind of visual debugging tool
Dialogue: 0,0:23:58.87,0:24:00.75,Default,,0,0,0,,for SpriteKit developers that we
Dialogue: 0,0:24:00.75,0:24:02.17,Default,,0,0,0,,provide for developers using
Dialogue: 0,0:24:02.17,0:24:03.03,Default,,0,0,0,,UIKit and AppKit.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:03.83,0:24:04.76,Default,,0,0,0,,So I'm pleased to announce that
Dialogue: 0,0:24:04.76,0:24:08.05,Default,,0,0,0,,in Xcode 9 SpriteKit is now a
Dialogue: 0,0:24:08.05,0:24:10.22,Default,,0,0,0,,first-class citizen in the View
Dialogue: 0,0:24:10.22,0:24:10.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Debugger.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:12.40,0:24:14.29,Default,,0,0,0,,When inspecting your view
Dialogue: 0,0:24:14.29,0:24:16.86,Default,,0,0,0,,hierarchy and Xcode finds a
Dialogue: 0,0:24:16.86,0:24:18.35,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit view, it will
Dialogue: 0,0:24:18.35,0:24:19.45,Default,,0,0,0,,automatically snapshot the
Dialogue: 0,0:24:19.45,0:24:20.97,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit scene hosted by that
Dialogue: 0,0:24:20.97,0:24:22.19,Default,,0,0,0,,view and bring that into the
Dialogue: 0,0:24:22.19,0:24:22.49,Default,,0,0,0,,debugger.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:23.35,0:24:25.20,Default,,0,0,0,,So now you'll see Sprites
Dialogue: 0,0:24:25.20,0:24:27.00,Default,,0,0,0,,rendered in the exploded 3D
Dialogue: 0,0:24:27.00,0:24:28.95,Default,,0,0,0,,visualization, along with all
Dialogue: 0,0:24:28.95,0:24:30.05,Default,,0,0,0,,the views in the hierarchy.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:31.44,0:24:33.32,Default,,0,0,0,,This is great for debugging
Dialogue: 0,0:24:33.51,0:24:34.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Sprite layout.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:35.19,0:24:36.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Also really handy for debugging
Dialogue: 0,0:24:36.68,0:24:38.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Sprite layout alongside View
Dialogue: 0,0:24:38.04,0:24:39.35,Default,,0,0,0,,layout for those projects where
Dialogue: 0,0:24:39.35,0:24:40.46,Default,,0,0,0,,you'd like to mix and match
Dialogue: 0,0:24:40.46,0:24:41.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Sprites and views for custom UI.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:46.12,0:24:47.26,Default,,0,0,0,,In the Debug Navigator you'll
Dialogue: 0,0:24:47.26,0:24:48.84,Default,,0,0,0,,see an entry for the SpriteKit
Dialogue: 0,0:24:48.84,0:24:50.31,Default,,0,0,0,,scene as a child of the view
Dialogue: 0,0:24:50.31,0:24:52.36,Default,,0,0,0,,that hosts it, and below that
Dialogue: 0,0:24:52.36,0:24:53.89,Default,,0,0,0,,scene you'll see all of the
Dialogue: 0,0:24:53.89,0:24:55.89,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit nodes that are in that
Dialogue: 0,0:24:55.89,0:24:56.72,Default,,0,0,0,,scene at runtime.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:57.48,0:25:00.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Select a SpriteKit node and you
Dialogue: 0,0:25:00.51,0:25:02.85,Default,,0,0,0,,can debug that by looking at the
Dialogue: 0,0:25:02.85,0:25:03.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Inspectors.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:04.85,0:25:06.37,Default,,0,0,0,,So now SpriteKit developers have
Dialogue: 0,0:25:06.37,0:25:07.99,Default,,0,0,0,,a visual tool for debugging
Dialogue: 0,0:25:07.99,0:25:08.80,Default,,0,0,0,,their SpriteKit scenes at
Dialogue: 0,0:25:08.80,0:25:08.98,Default,,0,0,0,,runtime.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:09.52,0:25:16.38,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:25:16.88,0:25:17.98,Default,,0,0,0,,But we didn't want to stop at
Dialogue: 0,0:25:19.78,0:25:21.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Sprites. SceneKit is a 3D
Dialogue: 0,0:25:21.94,0:25:22.73,Default,,0,0,0,,graphics framework.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:23.16,0:25:24.41,Default,,0,0,0,,It's great for building rich 3D
Dialogue: 0,0:25:24.41,0:25:26.10,Default,,0,0,0,,worlds and 3D games, as well as
Dialogue: 0,0:25:26.10,0:25:28.22,Default,,0,0,0,,custom 3D UI, so we wanted to
Dialogue: 0,0:25:28.22,0:25:30.17,Default,,0,0,0,,also provide a visual tool for
Dialogue: 0,0:25:30.17,0:25:33.14,Default,,0,0,0,,SceneKit developers, and so we
Dialogue: 0,0:25:33.14,0:25:33.40,Default,,0,0,0,,did.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:34.00,0:25:35.50,Default,,0,0,0,,SceneKit is now included as part
Dialogue: 0,0:25:35.50,0:25:37.05,Default,,0,0,0,,of the View Debugging Workflow.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:37.97,0:25:39.60,Default,,0,0,0,,When Xcode is inspecting a View
Dialogue: 0,0:25:39.60,0:25:40.75,Default,,0,0,0,,hierarchy that contains a
Dialogue: 0,0:25:40.75,0:25:42.66,Default,,0,0,0,,SceneKit view, it will snapshot
Dialogue: 0,0:25:42.66,0:25:44.04,Default,,0,0,0,,the SceneKit scene hosted by
Dialogue: 0,0:25:44.04,0:25:46.10,Default,,0,0,0,,that view and bring that in to
Dialogue: 0,0:25:46.10,0:25:46.93,Default,,0,0,0,,the debugger.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:47.26,0:25:50.87,Default,,0,0,0,,In the Debug Navigator you'll
Dialogue: 0,0:25:50.87,0:25:53.37,Default,,0,0,0,,see an entry for the SceneKit
Dialogue: 0,0:25:53.37,0:25:55.79,Default,,0,0,0,,scene as a child of the view
Dialogue: 0,0:25:55.79,0:25:56.39,Default,,0,0,0,,that hosts it.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:57.13,0:25:58.64,Default,,0,0,0,,But you may notice a difference
Dialogue: 0,0:25:58.64,0:25:59.70,Default,,0,0,0,,here, compared to the SpriteKit
Dialogue: 0,0:25:59.70,0:26:00.65,Default,,0,0,0,,example I just showed.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:01.67,0:26:04.14,Default,,0,0,0,,That SceneKit scene has no child
Dialogue: 0,0:26:04.14,0:26:04.63,Default,,0,0,0,,elements.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:04.83,0:26:06.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Where are all the SceneKit scene
Dialogue: 0,0:26:06.57,0:26:07.02,Default,,0,0,0,,nodes.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:07.78,0:26:10.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Also notice that in the Canvas
Dialogue: 0,0:26:10.44,0:26:11.96,Default,,0,0,0,,the 3D scene is just being
Dialogue: 0,0:26:11.96,0:26:13.00,Default,,0,0,0,,represented by a flattened
Dialogue: 0,0:26:13.00,0:26:13.52,Default,,0,0,0,,snapshot.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:16.20,0:26:17.43,Default,,0,0,0,,So why is this?
Dialogue: 0,0:26:18.11,0:26:20.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, to make 2D views in
Dialogue: 0,0:26:20.75,0:26:22.53,Default,,0,0,0,,Sprites explorable, Xcode
Dialogue: 0,0:26:22.53,0:26:24.07,Default,,0,0,0,,explodes them out in 3D.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:24.58,0:26:25.72,Default,,0,0,0,,But what should it do with 3D
Dialogue: 0,0:26:25.72,0:26:26.12,Default,,0,0,0,,content?
Dialogue: 0,0:26:27.53,0:26:28.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, we explored the latest
Dialogue: 0,0:26:28.80,0:26:30.10,Default,,0,0,0,,advances in 4D debugging
Dialogue: 0,0:26:30.10,0:26:31.15,Default,,0,0,0,,technology, but after some
Dialogue: 0,0:26:31.15,0:26:32.45,Default,,0,0,0,,accidents in the lab we thought
Dialogue: 0,0:26:32.45,0:26:34.28,Default,,0,0,0,,there must be an easier way, and
Dialogue: 0,0:26:34.28,0:26:34.61,Default,,0,0,0,,there was.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:35.03,0:26:36.12,Default,,0,0,0,,We already have a really
Dialogue: 0,0:26:36.12,0:26:37.87,Default,,0,0,0,,powerful 3D editor built right
Dialogue: 0,0:26:37.87,0:26:40.47,Default,,0,0,0,,into Xcode so we integrated the
Dialogue: 0,0:26:40.47,0:26:41.95,Default,,0,0,0,,SceneKit Editor with the View
Dialogue: 0,0:26:41.95,0:26:42.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Debugging Workflow.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:43.32,0:26:45.11,Default,,0,0,0,,Now just select a SceneKit scene
Dialogue: 0,0:26:45.11,0:26:46.87,Default,,0,0,0,,in the Debug Navigator and Xcode
Dialogue: 0,0:26:46.87,0:26:49.09,Default,,0,0,0,,will open the SceneKit Editor in
Dialogue: 0,0:26:49.39,0:26:50.56,Default,,0,0,0,,runtime debugging mode,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:51.04,0:26:53.02,Default,,0,0,0,,containing a snapshot of your 3D
Dialogue: 0,0:26:53.02,0:26:54.22,Default,,0,0,0,,scene from the runtime.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:55.46,0:26:56.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Now -- [applause] it's pretty
Dialogue: 0,0:26:56.61,0:26:56.72,Default,,0,0,0,,good.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:57.52,0:26:59.66,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:27:00.16,0:27:01.58,Default,,0,0,0,,So now you can use all the same
Dialogue: 0,0:27:01.58,0:27:02.59,Default,,0,0,0,,tools you're already familiar
Dialogue: 0,0:27:02.59,0:27:05.65,Default,,0,0,0,,with when creating a 3D scene to
Dialogue: 0,0:27:05.65,0:27:07.44,Default,,0,0,0,,inspect and debug that 3D scene.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:08.85,0:27:11.03,Default,,0,0,0,,You can move cameras around or
Dialogue: 0,0:27:11.03,0:27:12.66,Default,,0,0,0,,select alternate cameras.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:13.01,0:27:14.25,Default,,0,0,0,,You can zoom right out to get a
Dialogue: 0,0:27:14.25,0:27:15.71,Default,,0,0,0,,big picture view of that entire
Dialogue: 0,0:27:15.71,0:27:17.87,Default,,0,0,0,,scene, and you can visualize
Dialogue: 0,0:27:18.23,0:27:19.49,Default,,0,0,0,,objects in the scene that aren't
Dialogue: 0,0:27:19.49,0:27:21.02,Default,,0,0,0,,normally visible, like cameras
Dialogue: 0,0:27:21.02,0:27:24.07,Default,,0,0,0,,and view frustums and lights and
Dialogue: 0,0:27:24.07,0:27:25.29,Default,,0,0,0,,the light position and
Dialogue: 0,0:27:25.29,0:27:25.74,Default,,0,0,0,,direction.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:26.67,0:27:28.36,Default,,0,0,0,,You can explore the entire scene
Dialogue: 0,0:27:28.36,0:27:29.60,Default,,0,0,0,,graph in the outline view on the
Dialogue: 0,0:27:29.60,0:27:32.49,Default,,0,0,0,,left and you can select objects
Dialogue: 0,0:27:32.55,0:27:35.04,Default,,0,0,0,,in that 3D scene so you can hide
Dialogue: 0,0:27:35.04,0:27:36.44,Default,,0,0,0,,them or move them around to get
Dialogue: 0,0:27:36.44,0:27:37.51,Default,,0,0,0,,at objects that may be behind
Dialogue: 0,0:27:37.51,0:27:37.64,Default,,0,0,0,,them.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:38.08,0:27:39.14,Default,,0,0,0,,In fact, you can make any
Dialogue: 0,0:27:39.14,0:27:40.96,Default,,0,0,0,,modifications to that scene
Dialogue: 0,0:27:41.19,0:27:42.66,Default,,0,0,0,,using either the Canvas or the
Dialogue: 0,0:27:42.66,0:27:43.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Inspectors, which are all fully
Dialogue: 0,0:27:43.78,0:27:45.38,Default,,0,0,0,,operational, safe in the
Dialogue: 0,0:27:45.38,0:27:46.20,Default,,0,0,0,,knowledge that you won't be
Dialogue: 0,0:27:46.20,0:27:47.18,Default,,0,0,0,,affecting your runtime.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:47.63,0:27:48.84,Default,,0,0,0,,You'll just been modifying an
Dialogue: 0,0:27:48.84,0:27:49.77,Default,,0,0,0,,in-memory snapshot.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:50.68,0:27:51.73,Default,,0,0,0,,And if you'd like to save a copy
Dialogue: 0,0:27:51.73,0:27:53.38,Default,,0,0,0,,of that snapshot, that's easy,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:53.38,0:27:53.67,Default,,0,0,0,,too.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:53.76,0:27:55.18,Default,,0,0,0,,You can just export that out to
Dialogue: 0,0:27:55.18,0:27:57.41,Default,,0,0,0,,a SceneKit or a .dae file to
Dialogue: 0,0:27:57.41,0:27:58.48,Default,,0,0,0,,access at a later time.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:59.39,0:28:01.21,Default,,0,0,0,,So now SceneKit developers have
Dialogue: 0,0:28:01.21,0:28:02.74,Default,,0,0,0,,a visual debugging tool for
Dialogue: 0,0:28:02.74,0:28:04.61,Default,,0,0,0,,debugging their SceneKit scenes
Dialogue: 0,0:28:04.61,0:28:04.98,Default,,0,0,0,,at runtime.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:05.52,0:28:12.10,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:28:12.60,0:28:13.95,Default,,0,0,0,,So these are the enhancements
Dialogue: 0,0:28:13.95,0:28:16.09,Default,,0,0,0,,we've made for View debugging in
Dialogue: 0,0:28:16.12,0:28:16.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Xcode 9.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:17.24,0:28:18.14,Default,,0,0,0,,We've added View Controller
Dialogue: 0,0:28:18.14,0:28:20.03,Default,,0,0,0,,debugging, SpriteKit and
Dialogue: 0,0:28:20.10,0:28:20.93,Default,,0,0,0,,SceneKit debugging.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:21.80,0:28:22.71,Default,,0,0,0,,To take advantage of these
Dialogue: 0,0:28:22.71,0:28:24.19,Default,,0,0,0,,features your project just needs
Dialogue: 0,0:28:24.19,0:28:26.53,Default,,0,0,0,,to be running on one of the OS
Dialogue: 0,0:28:26.53,0:28:28.46,Default,,0,0,0,,releases from this week; iOS 11,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:28.88,0:28:30.98,Default,,0,0,0,,tvOS 11 or macOS High Sierra.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:35.38,0:28:36.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, I had mentioned that
Dialogue: 0,0:28:36.40,0:28:37.38,Default,,0,0,0,,graphics frameworks like
Dialogue: 0,0:28:37.57,0:28:39.91,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit and SceneKit are great
Dialogue: 0,0:28:39.95,0:28:41.21,Default,,0,0,0,,for building custom UI.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:41.67,0:28:42.81,Default,,0,0,0,,They're not just for building
Dialogue: 0,0:28:43.54,0:28:44.11,Default,,0,0,0,,games.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:44.74,0:28:47.17,Default,,0,0,0,,As an example, on the Xcode Team
Dialogue: 0,0:28:47.17,0:28:48.91,Default,,0,0,0,,we use these frameworks to build
Dialogue: 0,0:28:48.91,0:28:49.94,Default,,0,0,0,,our visual debuggers.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:50.69,0:28:52.84,Default,,0,0,0,,This is an example of the Memory
Dialogue: 0,0:28:52.84,0:28:53.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Graph Debugger that we
Dialogue: 0,0:28:53.63,0:28:54.63,Default,,0,0,0,,introduced last year.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:55.27,0:28:57.24,Default,,0,0,0,,It's showing a memory graph for
Dialogue: 0,0:28:57.24,0:28:58.24,Default,,0,0,0,,an app running on an iPhone.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:59.52,0:29:01.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, that visual memory graph,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:02.34,0:29:03.76,Default,,0,0,0,,we built that using SpriteKit.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:04.17,0:29:05.44,Default,,0,0,0,,So now we're really excited that
Dialogue: 0,0:29:05.44,0:29:06.82,Default,,0,0,0,,we can use our new SpriteKit
Dialogue: 0,0:29:07.15,0:29:08.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Debugger to debug our Memory
Dialogue: 0,0:29:08.58,0:29:09.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Graph Debugger.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:09.90,0:29:10.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Let me show you how that would
Dialogue: 0,0:29:11.77,0:29:11.90,Default,,0,0,0,,work.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:12.40,0:29:13.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's bring in another Xcode to
Dialogue: 0,0:29:13.80,0:29:15.54,Default,,0,0,0,,debug this first Xcode
Dialogue: 0,0:29:15.56,0:29:17.56,Default,,0,0,0,,[laughter].
Dialogue: 0,0:29:17.58,0:29:19.05,Default,,0,0,0,,It's taken a snapshot of that
Dialogue: 0,0:29:19.05,0:29:20.45,Default,,0,0,0,,view hierarchy and it now
Dialogue: 0,0:29:20.45,0:29:22.29,Default,,0,0,0,,includes all of the Sprites that
Dialogue: 0,0:29:22.29,0:29:23.86,Default,,0,0,0,,were shown as part of the Memory
Dialogue: 0,0:29:23.86,0:29:24.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Graph Debugger.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:24.84,0:29:26.29,Default,,0,0,0,,We can select an option to show
Dialogue: 0,0:29:26.29,0:29:27.38,Default,,0,0,0,,all the clip's content.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:27.38,0:29:28.34,Default,,0,0,0,,So now we can see all the
Dialogue: 0,0:29:28.34,0:29:29.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Sprites that are outside the
Dialogue: 0,0:29:29.32,0:29:30.31,Default,,0,0,0,,visible region.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:30.31,0:29:32.58,Default,,0,0,0,,And we can continue to zoom out
Dialogue: 0,0:29:32.58,0:29:34.28,Default,,0,0,0,,to get a big picture view of
Dialogue: 0,0:29:34.28,0:29:36.30,Default,,0,0,0,,that entire scene, a SpriteKit
Dialogue: 0,0:29:36.36,0:29:36.64,Default,,0,0,0,,scene.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:37.33,0:29:40.09,Default,,0,0,0,,So that's an example.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:40.09,0:29:41.46,Default,,0,0,0,,And this is actually what we do
Dialogue: 0,0:29:41.46,0:29:42.28,Default,,0,0,0,,on the Xcode Team.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:42.54,0:29:43.65,Default,,0,0,0,,We use our debuggers to debug
Dialogue: 0,0:29:43.65,0:29:43.98,Default,,0,0,0,,other debuggers.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:44.52,0:29:47.75,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Laughter ]
Dialogue: 0,0:29:48.25,0:29:50.96,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, to make these view
Dialogue: 0,0:29:50.96,0:29:52.29,Default,,0,0,0,,hierarchies exploded out in this
Dialogue: 0,0:29:52.29,0:29:56.29,Default,,0,0,0,,custom 3D visualization we used
Dialogue: 0,0:29:56.39,0:29:56.89,Default,,0,0,0,,SceneKit.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:57.41,0:29:58.95,Default,,0,0,0,,And so now we're doubly excited
Dialogue: 0,0:29:58.95,0:30:00.34,Default,,0,0,0,,that we can use our new SceneKit
Dialogue: 0,0:30:00.34,0:30:01.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Debugger to debug our View
Dialogue: 0,0:30:01.89,0:30:02.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Debugger.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:03.00,0:30:03.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Who wants to see that?
Dialogue: 0,0:30:05.02,0:30:06.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's bring in another Xcode to
Dialogue: 0,0:30:06.93,0:30:07.70,Default,,0,0,0,,debug the previous Xcode.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:08.52,0:30:10.52,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Laughter ]
Dialogue: 0,0:30:11.52,0:30:17.47,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:30:17.97,0:30:18.98,Default,,0,0,0,,So it's taken a snapshot of the
Dialogue: 0,0:30:18.98,0:30:20.18,Default,,0,0,0,,view hierarchy and exploded it
Dialogue: 0,0:30:20.18,0:30:22.48,Default,,0,0,0,,out in 3D, but now, because it's
Dialogue: 0,0:30:22.48,0:30:23.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Xcode 9, we have access to that
Dialogue: 0,0:30:23.95,0:30:24.83,Default,,0,0,0,,SceneKit scene.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:24.89,0:30:26.92,Default,,0,0,0,,So we can select that and we can
Dialogue: 0,0:30:26.92,0:30:29.26,Default,,0,0,0,,view that 3D custom
Dialogue: 0,0:30:29.43,0:30:30.73,Default,,0,0,0,,visualization in the SceneKit
Dialogue: 0,0:30:30.73,0:30:31.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Editor.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:31.91,0:30:33.58,Default,,0,0,0,,We can change cameras, change
Dialogue: 0,0:30:33.58,0:30:35.57,Default,,0,0,0,,perspectives to find the 3D
Dialogue: 0,0:30:35.57,0:30:36.65,Default,,0,0,0,,object in the scene that we're
Dialogue: 0,0:30:36.65,0:30:37.39,Default,,0,0,0,,looking to debug.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:37.39,0:30:40.94,Default,,0,0,0,,So that's the kind of fun we
Dialogue: 0,0:30:40.94,0:30:41.70,Default,,0,0,0,,have in Xcode.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:43.31,0:30:44.94,Default,,0,0,0,,So that's an example, what I've
Dialogue: 0,0:30:44.94,0:30:46.61,Default,,0,0,0,,shown you is an example of using
Dialogue: 0,0:30:46.61,0:30:49.42,Default,,0,0,0,,the new -- Xcode's new SceneKit
Dialogue: 0,0:30:49.54,0:30:51.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Debugger to debug the Xcode View
Dialogue: 0,0:30:51.97,0:30:53.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Debugger visualization, which
Dialogue: 0,0:30:53.29,0:30:55.42,Default,,0,0,0,,itself was SpriteKit debugging
Dialogue: 0,0:30:55.68,0:30:56.87,Default,,0,0,0,,the Memory Graph Debugger, which
Dialogue: 0,0:30:56.87,0:30:58.57,Default,,0,0,0,,itself was Memory Graph
Dialogue: 0,0:30:58.57,0:30:59.80,Default,,0,0,0,,debugging an app on the iPhone.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:00.34,0:31:01.71,Default,,0,0,0,,If you can follow along with all
Dialogue: 0,0:31:01.71,0:31:02.43,Default,,0,0,0,,that, then maybe you've got a
Dialogue: 0,0:31:02.43,0:31:02.98,Default,,0,0,0,,future on the Xcode Team
Dialogue: 0,0:31:03.02,0:31:03.52,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Laughter ]
Dialogue: 0,0:31:03.52,0:31:04.02,Default,,0,0,0,,.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:04.52,0:31:10.46,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:31:10.96,0:31:12.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, to give you a demonstration
Dialogue: 0,0:31:12.55,0:31:13.59,Default,,0,0,0,,of these new view debugging
Dialogue: 0,0:31:13.59,0:31:14.92,Default,,0,0,0,,enhancements, I'd like to invite
Dialogue: 0,0:31:14.92,0:31:15.49,Default,,0,0,0,,up Sebastian.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:15.49,0:31:15.96,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:16.52,0:31:20.10,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:31:20.60,0:31:21.24,Default,,0,0,0,,>> Thanks, Chris.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:22.23,0:31:22.86,Default,,0,0,0,,That's awesome.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:23.56,0:31:24.79,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm excited to show you some of
Dialogue: 0,0:31:24.85,0:31:26.21,Default,,0,0,0,,the new enhancements we made to
Dialogue: 0,0:31:26.21,0:31:28.00,Default,,0,0,0,,debugging in Xcode 9, but I'll
Dialogue: 0,0:31:28.00,0:31:29.83,Default,,0,0,0,,be using a slightly less complex
Dialogue: 0,0:31:29.83,0:31:30.92,Default,,0,0,0,,example than Chris just showed
Dialogue: 0,0:31:30.92,0:31:30.99,Default,,0,0,0,,you.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:36.12,0:31:37.42,Default,,0,0,0,,I'll actually be using the same
Dialogue: 0,0:31:37.60,0:31:38.75,Default,,0,0,0,,iOS app that Breckin used
Dialogue: 0,0:31:38.75,0:31:40.42,Default,,0,0,0,,earlier for his application, for
Dialogue: 0,0:31:40.42,0:31:42.25,Default,,0,0,0,,his demonstration, and it's
Dialogue: 0,0:31:42.25,0:31:45.43,Default,,0,0,0,,showing the solar system when
Dialogue: 0,0:31:46.70,0:31:47.85,Default,,0,0,0,,you launch the app, and it's
Dialogue: 0,0:31:47.85,0:31:49.11,Default,,0,0,0,,starting off with a 3D
Dialogue: 0,0:31:49.11,0:31:49.95,Default,,0,0,0,,visualization.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:50.47,0:31:51.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, using the button in the top
Dialogue: 0,0:31:51.75,0:31:53.40,Default,,0,0,0,,right corner the user can get
Dialogue: 0,0:31:53.40,0:31:56.31,Default,,0,0,0,,additional details about the
Dialogue: 0,0:31:56.53,0:31:58.28,Default,,0,0,0,,planets, and I've been working
Dialogue: 0,0:31:58.28,0:31:59.36,Default,,0,0,0,,on a very cool feature here.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:59.74,0:32:00.98,Default,,0,0,0,,My idea was to let the user
Dialogue: 0,0:32:00.98,0:32:03.26,Default,,0,0,0,,experience the gravity on the
Dialogue: 0,0:32:03.26,0:32:05.00,Default,,0,0,0,,different planets, so I built a
Dialogue: 0,0:32:05.00,0:32:06.30,Default,,0,0,0,,gravitySimulator using
Dialogue: 0,0:32:06.30,0:32:06.91,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:07.14,0:32:08.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Let me show you what that looks
Dialogue: 0,0:32:08.22,0:32:08.45,Default,,0,0,0,,like.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:09.60,0:32:11.44,Default,,0,0,0,,The gravitySimulator starts off
Dialogue: 0,0:32:11.44,0:32:13.12,Default,,0,0,0,,in zero gravity and the three
Dialogue: 0,0:32:13.12,0:32:14.75,Default,,0,0,0,,objects hover around in space.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:15.20,0:32:16.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, when the user swipes down
Dialogue: 0,0:32:16.46,0:32:18.45,Default,,0,0,0,,on the device's display, gravity
Dialogue: 0,0:32:18.45,0:32:19.74,Default,,0,0,0,,is activated and the three
Dialogue: 0,0:32:19.74,0:32:21.23,Default,,0,0,0,,objects begin to fall and
Dialogue: 0,0:32:21.23,0:32:22.40,Default,,0,0,0,,eventually hit the bottom of the
Dialogue: 0,0:32:22.40,0:32:23.42,Default,,0,0,0,,screen and bounce around.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:24.10,0:32:25.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Unfortunately, I got a bug
Dialogue: 0,0:32:25.18,0:32:26.32,Default,,0,0,0,,report that it's not behaving
Dialogue: 0,0:32:26.32,0:32:26.77,Default,,0,0,0,,quite right.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:27.27,0:32:28.55,Default,,0,0,0,,So let me swipe down and let's
Dialogue: 0,0:32:28.55,0:32:32.08,Default,,0,0,0,,observe what is going on.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:32.08,0:32:34.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh, now I understand what the
Dialogue: 0,0:32:34.35,0:32:35.28,Default,,0,0,0,,user was talking about.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:35.79,0:32:36.95,Default,,0,0,0,,So it looks like the gravity is
Dialogue: 0,0:32:36.95,0:32:38.80,Default,,0,0,0,,activated correctly, but the
Dialogue: 0,0:32:38.80,0:32:39.95,Default,,0,0,0,,objects don't actually hit the
Dialogue: 0,0:32:39.95,0:32:41.47,Default,,0,0,0,,bottom of the screen and bounce
Dialogue: 0,0:32:41.47,0:32:42.92,Default,,0,0,0,,around, they just go off screen.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:43.51,0:32:44.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's see if we can use the View
Dialogue: 0,0:32:44.48,0:32:45.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Debugger to better understand
Dialogue: 0,0:32:45.59,0:32:47.15,Default,,0,0,0,,what is going on here and try to
Dialogue: 0,0:32:47.15,0:32:47.97,Default,,0,0,0,,address the problem.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:49.40,0:32:50.38,Default,,0,0,0,,I'll invoke the View Debugger
Dialogue: 0,0:32:50.38,0:32:51.86,Default,,0,0,0,,using the button in the Debug
Dialogue: 0,0:32:51.86,0:32:54.83,Default,,0,0,0,,bar, and Xcode now fetches the
Dialogue: 0,0:32:54.83,0:32:56.87,Default,,0,0,0,,entire view hierarchy, including
Dialogue: 0,0:32:56.87,0:32:58.32,Default,,0,0,0,,the content of all SpriteKit
Dialogue: 0,0:32:58.32,0:32:59.44,Default,,0,0,0,,scenes that are part of the view
Dialogue: 0,0:32:59.44,0:32:59.90,Default,,0,0,0,,hierarchy.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:00.48,0:33:01.83,Default,,0,0,0,,On the left-hand side you get an
Dialogue: 0,0:33:01.83,0:33:03.05,Default,,0,0,0,,outline representation of that
Dialogue: 0,0:33:03.05,0:33:04.42,Default,,0,0,0,,hierarchy; whereas, in the
Dialogue: 0,0:33:04.42,0:33:05.49,Default,,0,0,0,,center you get a visual
Dialogue: 0,0:33:05.49,0:33:06.40,Default,,0,0,0,,representation.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:07.28,0:33:08.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, as you can see, the View
Dialogue: 0,0:33:08.47,0:33:09.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Debugger matches exactly what
Dialogue: 0,0:33:09.75,0:33:11.09,Default,,0,0,0,,you see on the device's display,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:11.52,0:33:12.63,Default,,0,0,0,,and you may be wondering how is
Dialogue: 0,0:33:12.68,0:33:14.22,Default,,0,0,0,,that particularly useful in this
Dialogue: 0,0:33:14.22,0:33:14.58,Default,,0,0,0,,case.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:15.57,0:33:17.01,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, if we recap what happened,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:17.20,0:33:18.58,Default,,0,0,0,,the three objects, they went off
Dialogue: 0,0:33:18.58,0:33:20.73,Default,,0,0,0,,screen, and by default the View
Dialogue: 0,0:33:20.73,0:33:22.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Debugger only shows you objects
Dialogue: 0,0:33:22.10,0:33:22.78,Default,,0,0,0,,that are visible.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:23.44,0:33:25.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, we can use this button here
Dialogue: 0,0:33:25.19,0:33:27.67,Default,,0,0,0,,in the bottom left corner to
Dialogue: 0,0:33:27.67,0:33:28.86,Default,,0,0,0,,also show content that is
Dialogue: 0,0:33:28.90,0:33:29.73,Default,,0,0,0,,currently being clipped.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:30.37,0:33:31.18,Default,,0,0,0,,So we can see that there's
Dialogue: 0,0:33:31.18,0:33:32.41,Default,,0,0,0,,actually a lot more going on
Dialogue: 0,0:33:32.41,0:33:33.36,Default,,0,0,0,,here than we can see on the
Dialogue: 0,0:33:33.36,0:33:34.24,Default,,0,0,0,,device's display.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:35.00,0:33:36.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Let me zoom out a little bit so
Dialogue: 0,0:33:36.07,0:33:37.95,Default,,0,0,0,,we can get a better overview.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:38.40,0:33:39.82,Default,,0,0,0,,And we actually found our three
Dialogue: 0,0:33:39.82,0:33:40.66,Default,,0,0,0,,objects down here.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:41.31,0:33:42.98,Default,,0,0,0,,So it looks like what's going on
Dialogue: 0,0:33:43.69,0:33:45.05,Default,,0,0,0,,is that the SpriteKit scene is
Dialogue: 0,0:33:45.05,0:33:46.56,Default,,0,0,0,,just too tall for the device's
Dialogue: 0,0:33:46.56,0:33:48.39,Default,,0,0,0,,display and by the time they hit
Dialogue: 0,0:33:48.39,0:33:49.26,Default,,0,0,0,,the bottom of the scene and
Dialogue: 0,0:33:49.26,0:33:50.65,Default,,0,0,0,,bounce around, they're already
Dialogue: 0,0:33:50.65,0:33:51.24,Default,,0,0,0,,off screen.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:52.54,0:33:53.73,Default,,0,0,0,,So let's see if we can address
Dialogue: 0,0:33:53.73,0:33:54.34,Default,,0,0,0,,this problem.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:54.97,0:33:56.42,Default,,0,0,0,,I'll select the SpriteKit scene
Dialogue: 0,0:33:56.42,0:33:57.43,Default,,0,0,0,,in the Debug Navigator on the
Dialogue: 0,0:33:57.43,0:33:58.92,Default,,0,0,0,,left-hand side and let's take a
Dialogue: 0,0:33:58.92,0:34:00.43,Default,,0,0,0,,look at its properties and see
Dialogue: 0,0:34:00.43,0:34:01.55,Default,,0,0,0,,if we can find one that we can
Dialogue: 0,0:34:01.55,0:34:01.95,Default,,0,0,0,,act on.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:02.31,0:34:03.94,Default,,0,0,0,,So you can see that we can get
Dialogue: 0,0:34:03.94,0:34:05.94,Default,,0,0,0,,additional details about the
Dialogue: 0,0:34:05.94,0:34:07.47,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit scene's size, it's
Dialogue: 0,0:34:07.47,0:34:09.71,Default,,0,0,0,,anchor point and it's scaleMode.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:10.34,0:34:11.66,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, the scaleMode is currently
Dialogue: 0,0:34:11.66,0:34:12.80,Default,,0,0,0,,set to Aspect Fill and that
Dialogue: 0,0:34:12.80,0:34:14.04,Default,,0,0,0,,looks a little bit suspicious.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:14.48,0:34:15.67,Default,,0,0,0,,I think there is a better aspect
Dialogue: 0,0:34:15.67,0:34:17.03,Default,,0,0,0,,fill to achieve what we're
Dialogue: 0,0:34:17.20,0:34:20.42,Default,,0,0,0,,trying to -- what we want the
Dialogue: 0,0:34:20.42,0:34:21.07,Default,,0,0,0,,scene to behave.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:21.11,0:34:22.60,Default,,0,0,0,,We want it to resize to actually
Dialogue: 0,0:34:22.60,0:34:23.75,Default,,0,0,0,,fit the device's display.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:25.25,0:34:26.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, I'm setting up the entire
Dialogue: 0,0:34:26.74,0:34:28.29,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit scene in the hosting
Dialogue: 0,0:34:28.29,0:34:29.83,Default,,0,0,0,,View Controller, and since the
Dialogue: 0,0:34:29.83,0:34:30.71,Default,,0,0,0,,view controllers are now
Dialogue: 0,0:34:30.71,0:34:31.88,Default,,0,0,0,,presented right along the view
Dialogue: 0,0:34:31.88,0:34:33.50,Default,,0,0,0,,hierarchy, it's very easy to get
Dialogue: 0,0:34:33.50,0:34:33.85,Default,,0,0,0,,to them.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:34.59,0:34:36.11,Default,,0,0,0,,I can simply select the
Dialogue: 0,0:34:36.20,0:34:37.68,Default,,0,0,0,,gravitySimulator View Controller
Dialogue: 0,0:34:37.68,0:34:38.76,Default,,0,0,0,,and the Debug Navigator on the
Dialogue: 0,0:34:38.76,0:34:40.68,Default,,0,0,0,,left-hand side, and using the
Dialogue: 0,0:34:40.68,0:34:42.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Inspector on the right-hand side
Dialogue: 0,0:34:42.34,0:34:43.70,Default,,0,0,0,,it's very easy to jump right to
Dialogue: 0,0:34:43.70,0:34:44.55,Default,,0,0,0,,the implementation.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:45.11,0:34:47.58,Default,,0,0,0,,I can use this button here that
Dialogue: 0,0:34:47.58,0:34:48.98,Default,,0,0,0,,is right next to the Class Name,
Dialogue: 0,0:34:49.82,0:34:50.81,Default,,0,0,0,,and we're here in the
Dialogue: 0,0:34:50.81,0:34:52.13,Default,,0,0,0,,implementation of this class.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:53.33,0:34:54.37,Default,,0,0,0,,And I'm setting up a couple of
Dialogue: 0,0:34:54.37,0:34:56.29,Default,,0,0,0,,things in viewDidLoad, so we're
Dialogue: 0,0:34:56.29,0:34:57.06,Default,,0,0,0,,here in viewDidLoad.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:57.06,0:34:58.21,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm first assigning the
Dialogue: 0,0:34:58.21,0:35:00.07,Default,,0,0,0,,planetName to the planetLabel at
Dialogue: 0,0:35:00.07,0:35:01.85,Default,,0,0,0,,the top, and here I'm setting up
Dialogue: 0,0:35:01.85,0:35:02.56,Default,,0,0,0,,the scaleMode.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:03.39,0:35:04.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, let me change the scaleMode
Dialogue: 0,0:35:05.32,0:35:07.45,Default,,0,0,0,,to something that will better
Dialogue: 0,0:35:08.43,0:35:10.54,Default,,0,0,0,,achieve what we're trying to do
Dialogue: 0,0:35:10.54,0:35:10.74,Default,,0,0,0,,here.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:11.02,0:35:12.43,Default,,0,0,0,,We want the scene to resize.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:12.90,0:35:14.51,Default,,0,0,0,,So resizeFill sounds like a much
Dialogue: 0,0:35:14.55,0:35:15.24,Default,,0,0,0,,better option here.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:16.20,0:35:17.77,Default,,0,0,0,,I'll now rerun and let's verify
Dialogue: 0,0:35:17.77,0:35:18.81,Default,,0,0,0,,if this actually addressed our
Dialogue: 0,0:35:18.81,0:35:19.22,Default,,0,0,0,,problem.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:20.51,0:35:22.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, we saw how easy it was to
Dialogue: 0,0:35:22.10,0:35:25.08,Default,,0,0,0,,visually inspect our application
Dialogue: 0,0:35:25.08,0:35:27.11,Default,,0,0,0,,that was using UIKit and
Dialogue: 0,0:35:27.11,0:35:28.51,Default,,0,0,0,,SpriteKit right along each
Dialogue: 0,0:35:28.51,0:35:28.85,Default,,0,0,0,,other.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:29.25,0:35:30.14,Default,,0,0,0,,We were able to get a good
Dialogue: 0,0:35:30.14,0:35:31.71,Default,,0,0,0,,understanding of where our three
Dialogue: 0,0:35:31.71,0:35:32.43,Default,,0,0,0,,objects went.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:33.11,0:35:34.32,Default,,0,0,0,,We were then able to select the
Dialogue: 0,0:35:34.32,0:35:35.72,Default,,0,0,0,,scene, find the property that we
Dialogue: 0,0:35:35.72,0:35:37.15,Default,,0,0,0,,wanted to act on, and use the
Dialogue: 0,0:35:37.15,0:35:38.69,Default,,0,0,0,,view controllers to jump right
Dialogue: 0,0:35:38.69,0:35:40.56,Default,,0,0,0,,to the implementation and make
Dialogue: 0,0:35:40.63,0:35:41.69,Default,,0,0,0,,that code change.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:42.31,0:35:43.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's verify we actually
Dialogue: 0,0:35:43.32,0:35:44.24,Default,,0,0,0,,addressed our problem here.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:45.18,0:35:46.35,Default,,0,0,0,,I'll go back to the planet
Dialogue: 0,0:35:46.35,0:35:48.24,Default,,0,0,0,,details and bring up the
Dialogue: 0,0:35:48.24,0:35:50.62,Default,,0,0,0,,gravitySimulator and now I'll
Dialogue: 0,0:35:50.62,0:35:52.18,Default,,0,0,0,,swipe down to activate gravity.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:53.29,0:35:53.95,Default,,0,0,0,,And here we go.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:54.13,0:35:54.96,Default,,0,0,0,,That looks a lot better.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:55.43,0:35:56.67,Default,,0,0,0,,The three objects bit the bottom
Dialogue: 0,0:35:56.67,0:35:57.70,Default,,0,0,0,,and you get a good understanding
Dialogue: 0,0:35:57.70,0:35:59.00,Default,,0,0,0,,of how strong the gravity really
Dialogue: 0,0:35:59.00,0:35:59.72,Default,,0,0,0,,is on this planet.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:01.04,0:36:03.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, there's one more thing.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:03.22,0:36:04.10,Default,,0,0,0,,I don't know if you already
Dialogue: 0,0:36:04.10,0:36:04.70,Default,,0,0,0,,noticed.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:05.22,0:36:06.39,Default,,0,0,0,,There's something going wrong in
Dialogue: 0,0:36:06.39,0:36:07.79,Default,,0,0,0,,the solar system in the front,
Dialogue: 0,0:36:08.23,0:36:09.73,Default,,0,0,0,,in the beginning of that.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:10.64,0:36:12.12,Default,,0,0,0,,There's something missing here.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:13.84,0:36:15.60,Default,,0,0,0,,There's a planet missing here,
Dialogue: 0,0:36:16.01,0:36:17.45,Default,,0,0,0,,and I'm not talking about Pluto.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:18.38,0:36:21.46,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm talking about Saturn, and
Dialogue: 0,0:36:21.46,0:36:22.87,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm very confident that my model
Dialogue: 0,0:36:22.87,0:36:24.07,Default,,0,0,0,,is set up correctly with all the
Dialogue: 0,0:36:24.07,0:36:25.03,Default,,0,0,0,,details about the different
Dialogue: 0,0:36:25.03,0:36:26.51,Default,,0,0,0,,planets, and since I'm using
Dialogue: 0,0:36:26.51,0:36:28.07,Default,,0,0,0,,SceneKit to build this 3D
Dialogue: 0,0:36:28.07,0:36:29.81,Default,,0,0,0,,visualization, something must be
Dialogue: 0,0:36:29.81,0:36:31.21,Default,,0,0,0,,incorrectly set up with my scene
Dialogue: 0,0:36:31.21,0:36:31.63,Default,,0,0,0,,graph.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:32.07,0:36:33.38,Default,,0,0,0,,So let's use the View Debugger
Dialogue: 0,0:36:33.77,0:36:35.75,Default,,0,0,0,,to take a look and find out what
Dialogue: 0,0:36:35.75,0:36:36.50,Default,,0,0,0,,happened to Saturn.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:37.87,0:36:38.87,Default,,0,0,0,,I'll again bring up the View
Dialogue: 0,0:36:38.87,0:36:40.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Debugger using the button in the
Dialogue: 0,0:36:40.25,0:36:40.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Debug bar.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:41.49,0:36:42.90,Default,,0,0,0,,And Xcode captures the view
Dialogue: 0,0:36:42.90,0:36:44.45,Default,,0,0,0,,hierarchy, including the content
Dialogue: 0,0:36:44.45,0:36:46.06,Default,,0,0,0,,of all SceneKit scenes that are
Dialogue: 0,0:36:46.06,0:36:47.04,Default,,0,0,0,,part of the view hierarchy.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:47.61,0:36:48.78,Default,,0,0,0,,And as Chris mentioned earlier,
Dialogue: 0,0:36:48.88,0:36:50.35,Default,,0,0,0,,they're now presented right
Dialogue: 0,0:36:50.39,0:36:52.15,Default,,0,0,0,,below the hosting SCN view in
Dialogue: 0,0:36:52.15,0:36:53.41,Default,,0,0,0,,the Debug Navigator on the
Dialogue: 0,0:36:53.41,0:36:54.06,Default,,0,0,0,,left-hand side.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:54.81,0:36:56.68,Default,,0,0,0,,And selecting it opens that
Dialogue: 0,0:36:56.68,0:36:58.93,Default,,0,0,0,,runtime snapshot of the scene in
Dialogue: 0,0:36:58.93,0:37:00.46,Default,,0,0,0,,the SceneKit Editor, which is in
Dialogue: 0,0:37:00.46,0:37:01.55,Default,,0,0,0,,runtime debugging mode.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:02.97,0:37:05.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, you can see that besides
Dialogue: 0,0:37:05.12,0:37:06.88,Default,,0,0,0,,the 3D world, it shows you
Dialogue: 0,0:37:06.88,0:37:07.90,Default,,0,0,0,,additional information.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:08.19,0:37:09.42,Default,,0,0,0,,In this case the wire frame
Dialogue: 0,0:37:09.42,0:37:10.71,Default,,0,0,0,,representation of this sphere
Dialogue: 0,0:37:10.71,0:37:12.20,Default,,0,0,0,,visualizes the light source that
Dialogue: 0,0:37:12.20,0:37:14.70,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm using to illuminate the
Dialogue: 0,0:37:14.70,0:37:15.36,Default,,0,0,0,,solar system.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:16.63,0:37:17.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Since we're currently not
Dialogue: 0,0:37:17.38,0:37:19.47,Default,,0,0,0,,debugging a lighting issue, I
Dialogue: 0,0:37:19.47,0:37:20.92,Default,,0,0,0,,can turn off the display of
Dialogue: 0,0:37:20.92,0:37:22.67,Default,,0,0,0,,lights using the Editor menu so
Dialogue: 0,0:37:22.67,0:37:24.05,Default,,0,0,0,,we can focus on the 3D world.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:24.05,0:37:27.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, let me increase the size of
Dialogue: 0,0:37:27.33,0:37:29.87,Default,,0,0,0,,the window here a little bit so
Dialogue: 0,0:37:29.94,0:37:31.23,Default,,0,0,0,,we have more space to work with.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:32.04,0:37:33.16,Default,,0,0,0,,On the left-hand side I can
Dialogue: 0,0:37:33.16,0:37:33.95,Default,,0,0,0,,bring up an outline
Dialogue: 0,0:37:33.95,0:37:35.03,Default,,0,0,0,,representation of the entire
Dialogue: 0,0:37:35.03,0:37:37.11,Default,,0,0,0,,scene graph, and when I expand
Dialogue: 0,0:37:37.11,0:37:38.82,Default,,0,0,0,,this graph, you can see all the
Dialogue: 0,0:37:38.82,0:37:40.16,Default,,0,0,0,,SceneKit nodes that I used to
Dialogue: 0,0:37:40.16,0:37:41.06,Default,,0,0,0,,build this screen in
Dialogue: 0,0:37:41.06,0:37:41.68,Default,,0,0,0,,visualization.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:43.08,0:37:44.62,Default,,0,0,0,,And looking down here we can see
Dialogue: 0,0:37:44.62,0:37:45.94,Default,,0,0,0,,that Saturn is actually part of
Dialogue: 0,0:37:45.94,0:37:48.52,Default,,0,0,0,,it, and selecting it gives us
Dialogue: 0,0:37:48.52,0:37:49.93,Default,,0,0,0,,additional details in the
Dialogue: 0,0:37:50.18,0:37:51.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Inspector on the right-hand
Dialogue: 0,0:37:51.16,0:37:51.42,Default,,0,0,0,,side.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:51.72,0:37:52.98,Default,,0,0,0,,In this case we can inspect the
Dialogue: 0,0:37:52.98,0:37:54.90,Default,,0,0,0,,material property and even take
Dialogue: 0,0:37:54.90,0:37:55.83,Default,,0,0,0,,a look at it in 3D.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:56.97,0:37:58.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, you can also see that it's
Dialogue: 0,0:37:58.56,0:38:00.00,Default,,0,0,0,,actually part of the 3D world.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:00.58,0:38:02.12,Default,,0,0,0,,And since the SceneKit Editor
Dialogue: 0,0:38:02.12,0:38:03.49,Default,,0,0,0,,visualizes the camera's view
Dialogue: 0,0:38:03.49,0:38:05.84,Default,,0,0,0,,frustum, it's very easy to
Dialogue: 0,0:38:05.84,0:38:06.98,Default,,0,0,0,,understand why we don't see it
Dialogue: 0,0:38:06.98,0:38:08.09,Default,,0,0,0,,on the device's display.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:08.09,0:38:09.57,Default,,0,0,0,,It's simply outside the area
Dialogue: 0,0:38:09.95,0:38:11.50,Default,,0,0,0,,that the camera can see.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:12.93,0:38:14.01,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, we don't have enough time
Dialogue: 0,0:38:14.01,0:38:15.65,Default,,0,0,0,,to go into the code and address
Dialogue: 0,0:38:15.65,0:38:17.23,Default,,0,0,0,,this problem right now, and I'd
Dialogue: 0,0:38:17.23,0:38:18.82,Default,,0,0,0,,actually like to have Breckin
Dialogue: 0,0:38:18.82,0:38:19.90,Default,,0,0,0,,look at the problem after this
Dialogue: 0,0:38:19.90,0:38:20.26,Default,,0,0,0,,session.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:20.68,0:38:22.30,Default,,0,0,0,,So what I can do now, I can
Dialogue: 0,0:38:22.60,0:38:23.98,Default,,0,0,0,,export the current state of this
Dialogue: 0,0:38:23.98,0:38:25.50,Default,,0,0,0,,snapshot using the Export button
Dialogue: 0,0:38:25.50,0:38:27.58,Default,,0,0,0,,in the top right corner and save
Dialogue: 0,0:38:27.58,0:38:28.74,Default,,0,0,0,,that to disk, and I can now
Dialogue: 0,0:38:28.74,0:38:31.37,Default,,0,0,0,,share that snapshot and other
Dialogue: 0,0:38:31.37,0:38:32.77,Default,,0,0,0,,people will be able to just open
Dialogue: 0,0:38:32.77,0:38:34.38,Default,,0,0,0,,that up and use it as a
Dialogue: 0,0:38:34.38,0:38:35.55,Default,,0,0,0,,reference to then go into the
Dialogue: 0,0:38:35.55,0:38:36.83,Default,,0,0,0,,code to address the problem.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:37.81,0:38:40.50,Default,,0,0,0,,So we were able to see how
Dialogue: 0,0:38:40.50,0:38:42.44,Default,,0,0,0,,useful it is to visually inspect
Dialogue: 0,0:38:42.44,0:38:44.11,Default,,0,0,0,,the 3D world that you build
Dialogue: 0,0:38:44.11,0:38:45.41,Default,,0,0,0,,using SceneKit to get a better
Dialogue: 0,0:38:45.41,0:38:46.70,Default,,0,0,0,,understanding of what is going
Dialogue: 0,0:38:46.70,0:38:47.77,Default,,0,0,0,,on in your application.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:48.13,0:38:49.73,Default,,0,0,0,,I think if you're using SceneKit
Dialogue: 0,0:38:49.99,0:38:51.84,Default,,0,0,0,,for your applications, you'll
Dialogue: 0,0:38:51.84,0:38:53.42,Default,,0,0,0,,really find it useful to
Dialogue: 0,0:38:53.42,0:38:54.70,Default,,0,0,0,,visually inspect the 3D world
Dialogue: 0,0:38:54.70,0:38:54.98,Default,,0,0,0,,you built.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:55.52,0:39:03.34,Default,,0,0,0,,[ Applause ]
Dialogue: 0,0:39:03.84,0:39:04.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Let me switch back to slides.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:09.07,0:39:09.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, let's recap what we went
Dialogue: 0,0:39:09.71,0:39:09.98,Default,,0,0,0,,over today.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:17.33,0:39:18.69,Default,,0,0,0,,First we introduced wireless
Dialogue: 0,0:39:18.75,0:39:19.34,Default,,0,0,0,,development.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:20.02,0:39:21.47,Default,,0,0,0,,It's a totally new development
Dialogue: 0,0:39:21.47,0:39:22.50,Default,,0,0,0,,in debugging experience
Dialogue: 0,0:39:22.50,0:39:23.69,Default,,0,0,0,,completely without a cable.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:23.69,0:39:24.89,Default,,0,0,0,,I think you will really love it.
